 has been removed for brevity.","pos":[14672,14760],"source":" The definition of the panels, alluded to by \"`...`\" below, has been removed for brevity."},{"content":"Tooling","pos":[15944,15951]},{"content":"By default, you'll probably want to target the broadest possible device family.","pos":[15953,16032]},{"content":"When you're ready to see how your app looks and lays out on a particular device, use the device preview toolbar in Visual Studio to preview your UI on a small or medium mobile device, on a PC, or on a large TV screen.","pos":[16033,16250]},{"content":"That way you can tailor and test your adaptive visual states:","pos":[16251,16312]},{"content":"visual studio 2015 device preview toolbar","pos":[16316,16357]},{"content":"You don’t have to make a decision up front about every device type that you'll support.","pos":[16402,16489]},{"content":"You can add an additional device size to your project later.","pos":[16490,16550]},{"content":"Adaptive scaling","pos":[16556,16572]},{"content":"Windows 10 introduces an evolution of the existing scaling model.","pos":[16574,16639]},{"content":"In addition to scaling vector content, there is a unified set of scale factors that provides a consistent size for UI elements across a variety of screen sizes and display resolutions.","pos":[16640,16824]},{"content":"The scale factors are also compatible with the scale factors of other operating systems such as iOS and Android.","pos":[16825,16937]},{"content":"This makes it easier to share assets between these platforms.","pos":[16938,16999]},{"content":"The Store picks the assets to download based in part of the DPI of the device.","pos":[17001,17079]},{"content":"Only the assets that best match the device are downloaded.","pos":[17080,17138]},{"content":"Common input handling","pos":[17144,17165]},{"content":"You can build a Universal Windows app using universal controls that handle various inputs such as mouse, keyboard, touch, pen, and controller (such as the Xbox controller).","pos":[17167,17339]},{"content":"Traditionally, inking has been associated only with pen input, but with Windows 10, you can ink with touch on some devices, and with any pointer input.","pos":[17340,17491]},{"content":"Inking is supported on many devices (including mobile devices) and can easily be incorporated with a just few lines of code.","pos":[17492,17616]},{"content":"The following APIs provide access to input:","pos":[17618,17661]},{"pos":[17667,17850],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>CoreIndependentInputSource<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/dn298460)</ept> is a new API that allows you to consume raw input on the main thread or a background thread.","source":"[**CoreIndependentInputSource**](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/dn298460) is a new API that allows you to consume raw input on the main thread or a background thread."},{"pos":[17855,18110],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>PointerPoint<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br242038)</ept> unifies raw touch, mouse, and pen data into a single, consistent set of interfaces and events that can be consumed on the main thread or background thread by using <bpt id=\"p3\">**</bpt>CoreInput.<ept id=\"p3\">**</ept>","source":"[**PointerPoint**](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br242038) unifies raw touch, mouse, and pen data into a single, consistent set of interfaces and events that can be consumed on the main thread or background thread by using **CoreInput.**"},{"pos":[18115,18328],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>PointerDevice<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br225633)</ept> is a device API that supports querying device capabilities so that you can determine what input modalities are available on the device.","source":"[**PointerDevice**](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br225633) is a device API that supports querying device capabilities so that you can determine what input modalities are available on the device."},{"pos":[18333,18566],"content":"The new <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>InkCanvas<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/dn858535)</ept> XAML control and <bpt id=\"p3\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p4\">**</bpt>InkPresenter<ept id=\"p4\">**</ept><ept id=\"p3\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/dn922011)</ept> Windows Runtime APIs allow you to access ink stroke data.","source":"The new [**InkCanvas**](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/dn858535) XAML control and [**InkPresenter**](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/dn922011) Windows Runtime APIs allow you to access ink stroke data."},{"content":"Writing code","pos":[18571,18583]},{"content":"Your programming language options for your <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Windows 10 project in Visual Studio<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/windows/apps/dn609832.aspx#target_win10)</ept> include Visual C++, C#, Visual Basic, and JavaScript.","pos":[18586,18802],"source":"Your programming language options for your [Windows 10 project in Visual Studio](https://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/windows/apps/dn609832.aspx#target_win10) include Visual C++, C#, Visual Basic, and JavaScript."},{"content":"For Visual C++, C#, and Visual Basic, you can use XAML for a full-fidelity, native UI experience.","pos":[18803,18900]},{"content":"For Visual C++ you can choose to draw with DirectX either instead of or as well as using XAML.","pos":[18901,18995]},{"content":"For JavaScript, your presentation layer will be HTML, and HTML is of course a cross-platform web standard.","pos":[18996,19102]},{"content":"Much of your code and UI will be universal and it will run the same way everywhere.","pos":[19103,19186]},{"content":"But for code tailored to particular device families, and for UI tailored to particular form factors, you'll have the option to use adaptive code and adaptive UI.","pos":[19187,19348]},{"content":"Let's look at these different cases.","pos":[19349,19385]},{"content":"Calling an API that's implemented by your target device family","pos":[19389,19451]},{"content":"Whenever you want to call an API, you'll need to know whether the API is implemented by the device family that your app is targeting.","pos":[19455,19588]},{"content":"If in doubt, you can look it up in the API reference documentation.","pos":[19589,19656]},{"content":"If you open the relevant topic and look at the Requirements section, you'll see what the implementing device family is.","pos":[19657,19776]},{"content":"Let's say that your app is targeting version 10.0.x.0 of the universal device family and you want to call members of the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Windows.UI.Core.SystemNavigationManager<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/dn893595)</ept> class.","pos":[19777,20008],"source":" Let's say that your app is targeting version 10.0.x.0 of the universal device family and you want to call members of the [**Windows.UI.Core.SystemNavigationManager**](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/dn893595) class."},{"content":"In this example, the device family is \"Universal\".","pos":[20009,20059]},{"content":"It's a good idea to further confirm that the class members that you want to call are also within your target, and in this case they are.","pos":[20060,20196]},{"content":"So in this example, you now know that the APIs are guaranteed to be present on every device that your app can be installed on, and you can call the APIs in your code just like you normally would.","pos":[20197,20392]},{"content":"As another example, imagine that your app is targeting version 10.0.x.0 of the Xbox device family, and the reference topic for an API that you want to call says that the API was introduced in version 10.0.x.0 of the Xbox device family.","pos":[20514,20749]},{"content":"In that case, again, the API is guaranteed to be present on every device that your app can be installed on.","pos":[20750,20857]},{"content":"So you would be able to call that API in your code in the normal way.","pos":[20858,20927]},{"content":"Note that Visual Studio's IntelliSense will not recognize APIs unless they are implemented by your app's target device family or any extension SDKs that you have referenced.","pos":[20929,21102]},{"content":"Consequently, if you haven't referenced any extension SDKs, you can be sure that any APIs that appear in IntelliSense must therefore be in your target device family and you can call them freely.","pos":[21103,21297]},{"content":"Calling an API that's NOT implemented by your target device family","pos":[21301,21367]},{"content":"There will be cases when you want to call an API, but your target device family is not listed in the documentation.","pos":[21371,21486]},{"content":"In that case you can opt to write adaptive code in order to call that API.","pos":[21487,21561]},{"content":"Writing adaptive code with the ApiInformation class","pos":[21565,21616]},{"content":"There are two steps to write adaptive code.","pos":[21620,21663]},{"content":"The first step is to make the APIs that you want to access available to your project.","pos":[21664,21749]},{"content":"To do that, add a reference to the extension SDK that represents the device family that owns the APIs that you want to conditionally call.","pos":[21750,21888]},{"content":"See <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Extension SDKs<ept id=\"p1\">](../porting/w8x-to-uwp-porting-to-a-uwp-project.md#extension-sdks)</ept>.","pos":[21889,21976],"source":" See [Extension SDKs](../porting/w8x-to-uwp-porting-to-a-uwp-project.md#extension-sdks)."},{"content":"The second step is to use the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Windows.Foundation.Metadata.ApiInformation<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/dn949001)</ept> class in a condition in your code to test for the presence of the API you want to call.","pos":[21978,22202],"source":"The second step is to use the [**Windows.Foundation.Metadata.ApiInformation**](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/dn949001) class in a condition in your code to test for the presence of the API you want to call."},{"content":"This condition is evaluated wherever your app runs, but it evaluates to true only on devices where the API is present and therefore available to call.","pos":[22203,22353]},{"pos":[22355,22532],"content":"If you want to call just a small number of APIs, you could use the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>ApiInformation.IsTypePresent<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/dn949016)</ept> method like this.","source":"If you want to call just a small number of APIs, you could use the [**ApiInformation.IsTypePresent**](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/dn949016) method like this."},{"content":"In this case we can be confident that the presence of the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>HardwareButtons<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/jj207557)</ept> class implies the presence of the <bpt id=\"p3\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p4\">**</bpt>CameraPressed<ept id=\"p4\">**</ept><ept id=\"p3\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/dn653805)</ept> event, because the class and the member have the same requirements info.","pos":[22921,23243],"source":"In this case we can be confident that the presence of the [**HardwareButtons**](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/jj207557) class implies the presence of the [**CameraPressed**](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/dn653805) event, because the class and the member have the same requirements info."},{"content":"But in time, new members will be added to already-introduced classes, and those members will have later \"introduced in\" version numbers.","pos":[23244,23380]},{"content":"In such cases, instead of using <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>IsTypePresent<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>, you can test for the presence of individual members by using <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>IsEventPresent<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept>, <bpt id=\"p3\">**</bpt>IsMethodPresent<ept id=\"p3\">**</ept>, <bpt id=\"p4\">**</bpt>IsPropertyPresent<ept id=\"p4\">**</ept>, and similar methods.","pos":[23381,23577],"source":" In such cases, instead of using **IsTypePresent**, you can test for the presence of individual members by using **IsEventPresent**, **IsMethodPresent**, **IsPropertyPresent**, and similar methods."},{"content":"Here's an example.","pos":[23578,23596]},{"content":"The set of APIs within a device family is further broken down into subdivisions known as API contracts.","pos":[23805,23908]},{"content":"You can use the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>ApiInformation.IsApiContractPresent<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> method to test for the presence of an API contract.","pos":[23909,24016],"source":" You can use the **ApiInformation.IsApiContractPresent** method to test for the presence of an API contract."},{"content":"This is useful if you want to test for the presence of a large number of APIs that all exist in the same version of an API contract.","pos":[24017,24149]},{"content":"Win32 APIs in the UWP","pos":[24381,24402]},{"content":"A UWP app or Windows Runtime Component written in C++/CX has access to the Win32 APIs that are part of the UWP.","pos":[24406,24517]},{"content":"These Win32 APIs are implemented by all Windows 10 device families.","pos":[24518,24585]},{"content":"Link your app with Windowsapp.lib.","pos":[24586,24620]},{"content":"Windowsapp.lib is an \"umbrella\" lib that provides the exports for the UWP APIs.","pos":[24621,24700]},{"content":"Linking to Windowsapp.lib will add to your app dependencies on dlls that are pre